<details class="disclosure-item">
<summary>My Story</summary>
<div class="content-block">


<hr class="rule dotted-blue-rule">

<p> I grew up in rural Maine in the 1980s, splitting my time between long bike rides and my Nintendo. I knew from a young age that I wanted to be a teacher.
</p>

<p>
My undergraduate degree was in writing and philosophy, and in my late 20s I was a high school English and history and history teacher in Pittsfield, Maine.

I loved being a teacher, and when I went into social work I committed to practicing through an educational lens. I take a lot of heart in a line from my personal hero, Carl Rogers:

> “The person who is educated is the one who has learned how to learn and change.”

I also gravitated toward the existential therapy of Irvin Yalom, which was very much in fashion at the time, and still is.

In my ten years of experience, I have worked with individuals, couples, and families—in person, in residential settings, online, and in people’s homes. I have also managed case managers.

Three years ago, I decided to work with men (and their families) exclusively. I write about this decision (and this professional focus) in my newsletter, _Field Notes_, which you can subscribe to below.

In my spare time, I enjoy camping, gaming, riding bikes with my kids, and vacationing with my family.


</p>



